<p>Most visualizations that use parts of the surrounding text (or its background) as color keys are <strong>scrollytelling</strong> projects. The color key is part of an overlay — and when the visualization changes, so does the overlay:</p>



<figure><video src="https://blog.datawrapper.de/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/CleanShot-2023-10-05-at-15.27.46.mp4" controls=""></video><figcaption><strong><a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2021-us-spending-recovery-inflation/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Bloomberg, 2021</a></strong> Including the color key in the article is a common tactic for scrollytelling like this one. </figcaption></figure>



